          sudo apt-get update
          sudo apt-get install -y \
            fonts-noto-cjk \
            fonts-noto-color-emoji \
            fonts-noto-core \
            fonts-liberation

      - name: Setup .NET
        uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v1
        with:
          dotnet-version: '8.0.x'

      - name: Run tests
        run: dotnet test --logger "trx;LogFileName=test-results.trx"

      - name: Publish test results
        uses: dorny/test-reporter@v1
        if: always()
        with:
          name: Test Results
          path: '**/test-results.trx'
          reporter: dotnet-trx
```

This comprehensive testing approach ensures OpenMaui's text rendering works correctly across all supported languages and scripts, providing a robust foundation for international applications.

---

> Font fallback isn't just a nice-to-have feature—it's the difference between displaying '你好' correctly and showing empty boxes to millions of users.

> The IBus integration enables seamless input for over 3 billion people who use CJK languages, making your application truly international.

> HarfBuzz transforms Unicode text into properly shaped glyphs, handling the complex rules of Arabic ligatures, Indic vowel reordering, and emoji sequences.

sections.content:
Input Method Editors (IMEs) are essential for typing languages that have more characters than keyboard keys. Chinese, Japanese, and Korean users rely on IMEs to convert phonetic input into the correct characters.

## Understanding IME Workflow

When a user types Chinese using Pinyin input:

1. User types "nihao" on the keyboard
2. IME shows composition text: "你好" (候選字)
3. User selects the correct characters from candidates
4. IME commits the final text to the application

During composition, the application must display **preedit text** (uncommitted characters) with proper styling, usually with an underline.

## IBus Integration in SkiaEntry

The `SkiaEntry` control implements IME support through native IBus integration:

```csharp
// From SkiaEntry - IME composition handling
private string _preeditText = string.Empty;
private int _preeditCursorPos = 0;

protected override void OnTextInput(TextInputEventArgs e)
{
    if (e.IsComposing)
    {
        // Handle preedit text during composition
        _preeditText = e.CompositionText;
        _preeditCursorPos = e.CompositionCursorPos;
        Invalidate();
    }
    else
    {
        // Commit final text
        InsertText(e.Text);
        _preeditText = string.Empty;
    }
}

protected override void OnDraw(SKCanvas canvas)
{
    // Draw normal text
    DrawTextContent(canvas);

    // Draw preedit text with underline
    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(_preeditText))
    {
        DrawPreeditText(canvas, _preeditText, _preeditCursorPos);
    }
}
```

## XIM Protocol Support

For compatibility with older systems and applications, OpenMaui also supports the XIM protocol:

```csharp
// XIM event handling pattern
public void HandleXIMEvent(XEvent xEvent)
{
    if (xEvent.type == XEventType.KeyPress)
    {
        // Filter through XIM first
        if (XFilterEvent(ref xEvent, window))
        {
            // Event handled by XIM
            return;
        }

        // Handle as normal key event
        HandleKeyPress(xEvent);
    }
}
```

## Cursor Position Management

IMEs need to know where to display candidate windows. OpenMaui provides cursor position information:

```csharp
// From SkiaEntry - cursor position for IME
public Rect GetCursorRect()
{
    var x = MeasureTextWidth(Text.Substring(0, CursorPosition));
    var y = Padding.Top;
    var height = FontSize * 1.2; // Line height

    return new Rect(x, y, 2, height);
}

public void UpdateIMECursorPosition()
{
    if (ibusContext != null)
    {
        var rect = GetCursorRect();
        // Convert to screen coordinates
        var screenRect = TransformToScreen(rect);
        ibusContext.SetCursorLocation(
            (int)screenRect.X,
            (int)screenRect.Y,
            (int)screenRect.Width,
            (int)screenRect.Height
        );
    }
}
```

## Testing IME Integration

Testing IME functionality requires actual input method frameworks:

```bash
# Install IBus and Chinese input
sudo apt install ibus ibus-pinyin

# Start IBus daemon
ibus-daemon -drx

# Set environment variables
export GTK_IM_MODULE=ibus
export QT_IM_MODULE=ibus
export XMODIFIERS=@im=ibus
```

In your application:

```csharp
// Test case for IME composition
[Fact]
public void Entry_HandlesIMEComposition()
{
    var entry = new SkiaEntry();

    // Simulate IME composition
    entry.HandleTextInput(new TextInputEventArgs
    {
        IsComposing = true,
        CompositionText = "你好",
        CompositionCursorPos = 2
    });

    Assert.Equal("你好", entry.PreeditText);
    Assert.Equal("", entry.Text); // Not committed yet

    // Simulate commit
    entry.HandleTextInput(new TextInputEventArgs
    {
        IsComposing = false,
        Text = "你好"
    });

    Assert.Equal("你好", entry.Text);
    Assert.Equal("", entry.PreeditText);
}
```

## Fcitx5 Compatibility

While IBus is most common, Fcitx5 users expect the same level of support. OpenMaui's abstraction layer handles both:

```csharp
public interface IInputMethodContext
{
    void SetCursorLocation(int x, int y, int width, int height);
    void FocusIn();
    void FocusOut();
    void Reset();
}

// IBus implementation
public class IBusInputContext : IInputMethodContext { ... }

// Fcitx5 implementation
public class Fcitx5InputContext : IInputMethodContext { ... }
```

The application detects which input method framework is active and uses the appropriate implementation.

Font fallback is the process of automatically switching to a different font when the current font doesn't contain a required glyph. Without it, users see empty boxes (□) or question marks (?) instead of their text.

## The Font Fallback Challenge

Consider this string: "Hello 世界 🌍"

- "Hello" might render with Roboto
- "世界" (Chinese) needs a CJK font like Noto Sans CJK
- "🌍" (emoji) requires a color emoji font like Noto Color Emoji

No single font contains all these glyphs. The system must detect missing glyphs and switch fonts **per character** or **per run** (consecutive characters from the same script).

## SkiaLabel's Font Fallback System

The `SkiaLabel` control implements intelligent font fallback:

```csharp
// From SkiaLabel - font fallback implementation
public class FontFallbackManager
{
    private readonly List<SKTypeface> _fallbackChain;

    public FontFallbackManager()
    {
        _fallbackChain = new List<SKTypeface>
        {
            // Primary font (user's choice)
            GetPrimaryFont(),

            // CJK fonts
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Sans CJK SC"),
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Sans CJK JP"),
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("WenQuanYi Micro Hei"),

            // Emoji fonts
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Color Emoji"),
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Segoe UI Emoji"),

            // Fallback for other scripts
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Sans"),
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("DejaVu Sans")
        };
    }

    public SKTypeface GetTypefaceForCharacter(char c, SKTypeface primary)
    {
        // Check if primary font has this glyph
        if (HasGlyph(primary, c))
            return primary;

        // Try fallback fonts
        foreach (var fallback in _fallbackChain)
        {
            if (fallback != null && HasGlyph(fallback, c))
                return fallback;
        }

        // Last resort: return primary (will show □)
        return primary;
    }

    private bool HasGlyph(SKTypeface typeface, char c)
    {
        var glyphs = new ushort[1];
        var text = c.ToString();
        return typeface.GetGlyphs(text, out glyphs) > 0 && glyphs[0] != 0;
    }
}
```

## Run-Based Rendering

For efficiency, OpenMaui groups consecutive characters that use the same font into **text runs**:

```csharp
// Text run detection
public class TextRun
{
    public string Text { get; set; }
    public SKTypeface Typeface { get; set; }
    public int StartIndex { get; set; }
    public int Length { get; set; }
}

public List<TextRun> SplitIntoRuns(string text, SKTypeface primaryFont)
{
    var runs = new List<TextRun>();
    var currentRun = new StringBuilder();
    var currentTypeface = primaryFont;
    var startIndex = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < text.Length; i++)
    {
        var c = text[i];
        var typeface = _fallbackManager.GetTypefaceForCharacter(c, primaryFont);

        if (typeface != currentTypeface && currentRun.Length > 0)
        {
            // Start new run
            runs.Add(new TextRun
            {
                Text = currentRun.ToString(),
                Typeface = currentTypeface,
                StartIndex = startIndex,
                Length = currentRun.Length
            });

            currentRun.Clear();
            startIndex = i;
            currentTypeface = typeface;
        }

        currentRun.Append(c);
    }

    // Add final run
    if (currentRun.Length > 0)
    {
        runs.Add(new TextRun
        {
            Text = currentRun.ToString(),
            Typeface = currentTypeface,
            StartIndex = startIndex,
            Length = currentRun.Length
        });
    }

    return runs;
}
```

## Drawing with Font Fallback

The rendering code uses text runs:

```csharp
// From SkiaLabel - rendering with fallback
protected override void OnDraw(SKCanvas canvas)
{
    var runs = SplitIntoRuns(Text, GetPrimaryTypeface());
    float x = (float)Padding.Left;
    float y = (float)(Padding.Top + FontSize);

    foreach (var run in runs)
    {
        using var paint = new SKPaint
        {
            Color = TextColor.ToSKColor(),
            TextSize = (float)FontSize,
            Typeface = run.Typeface,
            IsAntialias = true,
            SubpixelText = true
        };

        canvas.DrawText(run.Text, x, y, paint);
        x += paint.MeasureText(run.Text);
    }
}
```

## Font Discovery on Linux

OpenMaui uses Fontconfig to discover available fonts:

```csharp
public class LinuxFontDiscovery
{
    [DllImport("libfontconfig.so.1")]
    private static extern IntPtr FcConfigGetCurrent();

    [DllImport("libfontconfig.so.1")]
    private static extern IntPtr FcPatternCreate();

    public List<string> GetAvailableFonts()
    {
        var fonts = new List<string>();
        var config = FcConfigGetCurrent();

        // Query fontconfig for available fonts
        // Implementation details...

        return fonts;
    }

    public string FindBestFontForScript(UnicodeScript script)
    {
        return script switch
        {
            UnicodeScript.Han => FindFont("Noto Sans CJK SC", "WenQuanYi"),
            UnicodeScript.Hiragana => FindFont("Noto Sans CJK JP"),
            UnicodeScript.Arabic => FindFont("Noto Sans Arabic"),
            UnicodeScript.Devanagari => FindFont("Noto Sans Devanagari"),
            _ => "Noto Sans"
        };
    }
}
```

## Emoji Font Handling

Emoji fonts require special handling because they're often color fonts (CBDT/COLR tables):

```csharp
public SKTypeface GetEmojiTypeface()
{
    // Try color emoji fonts first
    var colorEmoji = SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Color Emoji");
    if (colorEmoji != null)
        return colorEmoji;

    // Fallback to monochrome emoji
    return SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Emoji");
}

public bool IsEmoji(char c)
{
    // Basic emoji detection
    return (c >= 0x1F300 && c <= 0x1F9FF) || // Misc Symbols and Pictographs
           (c >= 0x2600 && c <= 0x26FF) ||   // Misc Symbols
           (c >= 0x2700 && c <= 0x27BF);     // Dingbats
}
```

## Performance Optimization

Font fallback can be expensive. OpenMaui caches font lookup results:

```csharp
private readonly Dictionary<char, SKTypeface> _glyphCache = new();

public SKTypeface GetTypefaceForCharacterCached(char c, SKTypeface primary)
{
    if (_glyphCache.TryGetValue(c, out var cached))
        return cached;

    var typeface = GetTypefaceForCharacter(c, primary);
    _glyphCache[c] = typeface;
    return typeface;
}
```

This reduces font lookups from O(n×m) to O(n) where n is text length and m is fallback chain length.

HarfBuzz is the industry-standard text shaping engine used by Chrome, Firefox, Android, and most modern text rendering systems. It transforms Unicode text into properly positioned glyphs, handling the complex rules of different writing systems.

## Why Text Shaping Matters

Consider Arabic text "مرحبا" (hello). The same letter has different forms depending on its position:

- **Isolated form**: م
- **Initial form**: مـ (when starting a word)
- **Medial form**: ـمـ (in the middle)
- **Final form**: ـم (at the end)

HarfBuzz applies these contextual substitutions automatically. Without shaping, Arabic text looks disconnected and wrong.

## HarfBuzz Integration

OpenMaui uses HarfBuzzSharp 7.3.0.3 for text shaping:

```csharp
using HarfBuzzSharp;

public class TextShaper
{
    public ShapedGlyphs ShapeText(string text, SKTypeface typeface, float fontSize)
    {
        // Create HarfBuzz font from SKTypeface
        using var blob = typeface.OpenStream(out var ttcIndex).AsHarfBuzzBlob();
        using var face = new Face(blob, ttcIndex);
        using var font = new Font(face);
        font.SetScale((int)fontSize, (int)fontSize);

        // Create buffer with text
        using var buffer = new HarfBuzzSharp.Buffer();
        buffer.AddUtf16(text);
        buffer.GuessSegmentProperties();

        // Shape the text
        font.Shape(buffer);

        // Extract glyph information
        var glyphInfos = buffer.GlyphInfos;
        var glyphPositions = buffer.GlyphPositions;

        var result = new ShapedGlyphs();
        float xPos = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < glyphInfos.Length; i++)
        {
            var info = glyphInfos[i];
            var pos = glyphPositions[i];

            result.Glyphs.Add(new ShapedGlyph
            {
                GlyphId = info.Codepoint,
                Cluster = info.Cluster,
                XOffset = xPos + pos.XOffset / 64f,
                YOffset = pos.YOffset / 64f,
                XAdvance = pos.XAdvance / 64f,
                YAdvance = pos.YAdvance / 64f
            });

            xPos += pos.XAdvance / 64f;
        }

        return result;
    }
}

public class ShapedGlyphs
{
    public List<ShapedGlyph> Glyphs { get; set; } = new();
}

public class ShapedGlyph
{
    public uint GlyphId { get; set; }
    public uint Cluster { get; set; }
    public float XOffset { get; set; }
    public float YOffset { get; set; }
    public float XAdvance { get; set; }
    public float YAdvance { get; set; }
}
```

## Rendering Shaped Text

Once text is shaped, we render it using SkiaSharp:

```csharp
public void DrawShapedText(SKCanvas canvas, ShapedGlyphs shaped, 
                           SKTypeface typeface, float fontSize, 
                           SKColor color, float x, float y)
{
    using var paint = new SKPaint
    {
        Typeface = typeface,
        TextSize = fontSize,
        Color = color,
        IsAntialias = true,
        SubpixelText = true
    };

    // Convert glyphs to ushort array
    var glyphIds = shaped.Glyphs.Select(g => (ushort)g.GlyphId).ToArray();
    var positions = shaped.Glyphs.Select(g => 
        new SKPoint(x + g.XOffset, y + g.YOffset)
    ).ToArray();

    // Draw positioned glyphs
    canvas.DrawPositionedText(glyphIds, positions, paint);
}
```

## Script Detection

HarfBuzz needs to know the script (writing system) to apply correct shaping rules:

```csharp
public class ScriptDetector
{
    public static Script DetectScript(string text)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(text))
            return Script.Latin;

        var firstChar = text[0];

        // Arabic
        if (firstChar >= 0x0600 && firstChar <= 0x06FF)
            return Script.Arabic;

        // Hebrew
        if (firstChar >= 0x0590 && firstChar <= 0x05FF)
            return Script.Hebrew;

        // Devanagari
        if (firstChar >= 0x0900 && firstChar <= 0x097F)
            return Script.Devanagari;

        // Thai
        if (firstChar >= 0x0E00 && firstChar <= 0x0E7F)
            return Script.Thai;

        // CJK
        if (firstChar >= 0x4E00 && firstChar <= 0x9FFF)
            return Script.Han;

        return Script.Latin;
    }
}

public enum Script
{
    Latin,
    Arabic,
    Hebrew,
    Devanagari,
    Thai,
    Han,
    Hiragana,
    Katakana
}
```

## Direction Detection (BiDi)

Bidirectional text (mixing left-to-right and right-to-left) requires special handling:

```csharp
public class BiDiAnalyzer
{
    public Direction GetTextDirection(string text)
    {
        // Check for RTL characters
        foreach (var c in text)
        {
            if (IsRTL(c))
                return Direction.RightToLeft;
        }
        return Direction.LeftToRight;
    }

    private bool IsRTL(char c)
    {
        return (c >= 0x0590 && c <= 0x05FF) || // Hebrew
               (c >= 0x0600 && c <= 0x06FF) || // Arabic
               (c >= 0x0700 && c <= 0x074F);   // Syriac
    }
}

public enum Direction
{
    LeftToRight,
    RightToLeft
}
```

## Ligatures and Contextual Forms

HarfBuzz automatically applies ligatures (like "fi" → "ﬁ") and contextual forms:

```csharp
// Enable/disable OpenType features
public ShapedGlyphs ShapeWithFeatures(string text, SKTypeface typeface, 
                                      float fontSize, Feature[] features)
{
    using var blob = typeface.OpenStream(out var ttcIndex).AsHarfBuzzBlob();
    using var face = new Face(blob, ttcIndex);
    using var font = new Font(face);
    font.SetScale((int)fontSize, (int)fontSize);

    using var buffer = new HarfBuzzSharp.Buffer();
    buffer.AddUtf16(text);
    buffer.GuessSegmentProperties();

    // Apply features
    font.Shape(buffer, features);

    return ExtractGlyphs(buffer);
}

// Example: Disable ligatures
var features = new[]
{
    new Feature(Tag.Parse("liga"), 0, 0, uint.MaxValue)
};
var shaped = ShapeWithFeatures("difficult", typeface, 16, features);
```

## Emoji Sequences

Emoji sequences (like 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦) use zero-width joiners. HarfBuzz handles these correctly:

```csharp
public bool IsEmojiSequence(string text, int index)
{
    if (index + 1 >= text.Length)
        return false;

    // Check for zero-width joiner
    return text[index + 1] == '\u200D';
}

// HarfBuzz automatically shapes emoji sequences
var family = "👨\u200D👩\u200D👧\u200D👦";
var shaped = ShapeText(family, emojiTypeface, 24);
// Results in a single glyph for the family emoji
```

## Performance Considerations

Text shaping is computationally expensive. OpenMaui caches shaped results:

```csharp
public class ShapingCache
{
    private readonly Dictionary<ShapingKey, ShapedGlyphs> _cache = new();

    public ShapedGlyphs GetOrShape(string text, SKTypeface typeface, float fontSize)
    {
        var key = new ShapingKey(text, typeface, fontSize);

        if (_cache.TryGetValue(key, out var cached))
            return cached;

        var shaped = _shaper.ShapeText(text, typeface, fontSize);
        _cache[key] = shaped;
        return shaped;
    }
}

record ShapingKey(string Text, SKTypeface Typeface, float FontSize);
```

This dramatically improves performance for repeated text rendering, especially in lists and scrolling views.

Emoji support is more complex than it appears. Modern emoji use multiple Unicode codepoints, skin tone modifiers, and zero-width joiners to create composite glyphs.

## Unicode Emoji Fundamentals

Emoji come in several forms:

**Simple Emoji**: Single codepoint
```csharp
var heart = "❤️"; // U+2764 + U+FE0F (variation selector)
var smile = "😀"; // U+1F600
```

**Emoji with Skin Tone Modifiers**:
```csharp
var wave = "👋"; // U+1F44B
var waveDark = "👋🏿"; // U+1F44B + U+1F3FF (dark skin tone)
```

**Zero-Width Joiner (ZWJ) Sequences**:
```csharp
var family = "👨‍👩‍👧‍👦"; // Man + ZWJ + Woman + ZWJ + Girl + ZWJ + Boy
var femaleDoctor = "👩‍⚕️"; // Woman + ZWJ + Medical Symbol
```

## Emoji Detection

OpenMaui implements comprehensive emoji detection:

```csharp
public class EmojiDetector
{
    public bool IsEmoji(int codepoint)
    {
        return IsInEmojiRange(codepoint) || 
               IsEmojiModifier(codepoint) || 
               IsEmojiComponent(codepoint);
    }

    private bool IsInEmojiRange(int cp)
    {
        return (cp >= 0x1F600 && cp <= 0x1F64F) || // Emoticons
               (cp >= 0x1F300 && cp <= 0x1F5FF) || // Misc Symbols and Pictographs
               (cp >= 0x1F680 && cp <= 0x1F6FF) || // Transport and Map
               (cp >= 0x1F900 && cp <= 0x1F9FF) || // Supplemental Symbols
               (cp >= 0x2600 && cp <= 0x26FF) ||   // Misc symbols
               (cp >= 0x2700 && cp <= 0x27BF) ||   // Dingbats
               (cp >= 0xFE00 && cp <= 0xFE0F);     // Variation Selectors
    }

    private bool IsEmojiModifier(int cp)
    {
        return cp >= 0x1F3FB && cp <= 0x1F3FF; // Skin tone modifiers
    }

    private bool IsEmojiComponent(int cp)
    {
        return cp == 0x200D || // Zero-width joiner
               cp == 0xFE0F;   // Variation Selector-16
    }

    public List<EmojiSequence> FindEmojis(string text)
    {
        var emojis = new List<EmojiSequence>();
        int i = 0;

        while (i < text.Length)
        {
            if (char.IsHighSurrogate(text[i]))
            {
                var codepoint = char.ConvertToUtf32(text, i);
                if (IsEmoji(codepoint))
                {
                    var sequence = ExtractEmojiSequence(text, i);
                    emojis.Add(sequence);
                    i = sequence.EndIndex;
                    continue;
                }
                i += 2; // Surrogate pair
            }
            else
            {
                i++;
            }
        }

        return emojis;
    }

    private EmojiSequence ExtractEmojiSequence(string text, int startIndex)
    {
        int endIndex = startIndex;
        var sequence = new StringBuilder();

        // Extract emoji and any following modifiers/joiners
        while (endIndex < text.Length)
        {
            var c = text[endIndex];

            if (char.IsHighSurrogate(c) && endIndex + 1 < text.Length)
            {
                var cp = char.ConvertToUtf32(text, endIndex);
                if (IsEmoji(cp) || IsEmojiModifier(cp))
                {
                    sequence.Append(c);
                    sequence.Append(text[endIndex + 1]);
                    endIndex += 2;
                    continue;
                }
            }

            if (IsEmojiComponent(c))
            {
                sequence.Append(c);
                endIndex++;
                continue;
            }

            break;
        }

        return new EmojiSequence
        {
            Text = sequence.ToString(),
            StartIndex = startIndex,
            EndIndex = endIndex
        };
    }
}

public class EmojiSequence
{
    public string Text { get; set; }
    public int StartIndex { get; set; }
    public int EndIndex { get; set; }
}
```

## Color Emoji Rendering

Color emoji fonts use special tables (CBDT, COLR, SVG):

```csharp
public class EmojiRenderer
{
    private SKTypeface _colorEmojiFont;

    public EmojiRenderer()
    {
        // Load color emoji font
        _colorEmojiFont = SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Noto Color Emoji") ??
                         SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Apple Color Emoji") ??
                         SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Segoe UI Emoji");
    }

    public void DrawEmoji(SKCanvas canvas, string emoji, float x, float y, float size)
    {
        using var paint = new SKPaint
        {
            Typeface = _colorEmojiFont,
            TextSize = size,
            IsAntialias = true,
            SubpixelText = true
        };

        // Color emoji fonts handle color internally
        canvas.DrawText(emoji, x, y, paint);
    }
}
```

## Emoji Picker Integration

OpenMaui's text controls can integrate with the system emoji picker:

```csharp
// From SkiaEntry - emoji picker support
public void ShowEmojiPicker()
{
    // On Linux, use IBus emoji picker
    if (HasIBus())
    {
        // Ctrl+. or Ctrl+; triggers IBus emoji picker
        SimulateKeyPress(Key.Period, ModifierKeys.Control);
    }
    else
    {
        // Show custom emoji picker
        var picker = new EmojiPickerDialog();
        picker.EmojiSelected += (s, emoji) =>
        {
            InsertText(emoji);
        };
        picker.Show();
    }
}
```

## Emoji Text Measurement

Emoji sequences must be measured as a single unit:

```csharp
public float MeasureText(string text)
{
    var detector = new EmojiDetector();
    var emojis = detector.FindEmojis(text);

    float totalWidth = 0;
    int lastIndex = 0;

    foreach (var emoji in emojis)
    {
        // Measure text before emoji
        if (emoji.StartIndex > lastIndex)
        {
            var beforeText = text.Substring(lastIndex, emoji.StartIndex - lastIndex);
            totalWidth += MeasureTextSegment(beforeText, _regularFont);
        }

        // Measure emoji
        totalWidth += MeasureTextSegment(emoji.Text, _emojiFont);
        lastIndex = emoji.EndIndex;
    }

    // Measure remaining text
    if (lastIndex < text.Length)
    {
        var remainingText = text.Substring(lastIndex);
        totalWidth += MeasureTextSegment(remainingText, _regularFont);
    }

    return totalWidth;
}

private float MeasureTextSegment(string text, SKTypeface font)
{
    using var paint = new SKPaint
    {
        Typeface = font,
        TextSize = (float)FontSize
    };
    return paint.MeasureText(text);
}
```

## Unicode Normalization

Different Unicode representations can look identical but have different codepoints:

```csharp
public class UnicodeNormalizer
{
    public string Normalize(string text)
    {
        // Use NFC (Canonical Decomposition, followed by Canonical Composition)
        return text.Normalize(NormalizationForm.FormC);
    }

    public bool AreEquivalent(string text1, string text2)
    {
        return Normalize(text1) == Normalize(text2);
    }
}

// Example:
var e1 = "é"; // Single codepoint U+00E9
var e2 = "é"; // e (U+0065) + combining acute accent (U+0301)
// These look identical but text1.Length != text2.Length
// After normalization, they're equal
```

## Grapheme Cluster Boundaries

A grapheme cluster is what users perceive as a single character:

```csharp
public class GraphemeClusterIterator
{
    public List<string> GetGraphemeClusters(string text)
    {
        var clusters = new List<string>();
        var enumerator = StringInfo.GetTextElementEnumerator(text);

        while (enumerator.MoveNext())
        {
            clusters.Add(enumerator.GetTextElement());
        }

        return clusters;
    }
}

// Example:
var text = "👨‍👩‍👧‍👦Hello";
var clusters = iterator.GetGraphemeClusters(text);
// clusters[0] = "👨‍👩‍👧‍👦" (one grapheme cluster)
// clusters[1] = "H"
// clusters[2] = "e"
// etc.
```

This is crucial for cursor movement, text selection, and backspace behavior in text editors.

Chinese, Japanese, and Korean (CJK) languages present unique challenges for text input. With thousands of characters and limited keyboard keys, these languages rely heavily on Input Method Editors (IMEs).

## CJK Input Methods

**Chinese Input Methods:**
- **Pinyin**: Phonetic input ("nihao" → 你好)
- **Wubi**: Shape-based input for faster typing
- **Cangjie**: Traditional Chinese input method
- **Handwriting**: Touch/stylus input

**Japanese Input Methods:**
- **Romaji**: Type "konnichiwa" → こんにちは → 今日は
- **Kana**: Direct hiragana/katakana input
- **Flick input**: Mobile touch input

**Korean Input Methods:**
- **Hangul**: Automatic jamo composition (ㄱ + ㅏ + ㅇ → 강)
- **2-Set/3-Set**: Different keyboard layouts

